{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8df97b7087f055a7", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2605.06407 ===\n# \\ WavCube: A Unified SSL-Derived Latent  Representation for   Speech Understanding, Reconstruction, and Generation\narXiv: 2605.06407\nAuthors: \nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavCube introduces a compact 128-dimensional continuous latent representation that unifies speech understanding, reconstruction, and generation within a single space by infusing acoustic details into a distilled semantic manifold.\n  2. A compress-then-enrich two-stage learning recipe is proposed to resolve the high-dimensional redundancy and acoustic deficit inherent in SSL features, systematically transforming them into unified representations.\n  3. The compress stage utilizes a semantic auto-encoder bottleneck to distill frozen WavLM features into a compact, diffusion-friendly subspace while filtering off-manifold redundancy.\n  4. The enrich stage injects fine-grained acoustic details via end-to-end speech reconstruction while a semantic anchoring loss prevents drift from the original semantic manifold.\n  5. Extensive evaluations show WavCube closely approaches WavLM performance on SUPERB despite an 8x dimensional compression while matching acoustic representations in reconstruction fidelity.\n  6. WavCube achieves state-of-the-art zero-shot TTS performance with significantly faster diffusion training convergence compared to existing acoustic baselines.\n  7. WavCube consistently excels across diverse SUPERB-SG generation tasks, including speech enhancement, separation, and voice conversion.\n=== 2110.13900 ===\n# WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing\narXiv: 2110.13900\nAuthors: Sanyuan Chen, Chengyi Wang, Zhengyang Chen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Jinyu Li, Naoyuki Kanda, Takuya Yoshioka, Xiong Xiao, Jian Wu, Long Zhou, Shuo Ren, Yanmin Qian, Yao Qian, Jian Wu, Michael Zeng, Xiangzhan Yu, Furu Wei\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavLM introduces a general pre-trained model for full stack speech processing tasks, moving beyond the focus on specific task groups like ASR in prior self-supervised learning works.\n  2. A masked speech denoising and prediction framework is proposed to jointly learn speech content modeling and denoising, effectively improving performance on non-ASR tasks such as speaker verification, diarization, and separation.\n  3. Gated relative position bias is integrated into the Transformer structure to adaptively adjust relative position biases based on current speech content, enhancing sequence ordering capture and ASR performance.\n  4. The self-supervised speech pre-training data is scaled up to 94k hours from diverse domains, alleviating audiobook data bias and improving model robustness.\n  5. State-of-the-art results are achieved on the SUPERB benchmark and representative benchmarks for speaker verification, speech separation, and speaker diarization, with models and code publicly released.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散\n=== 2604.17852 ===\n# LLM-Codec: Neural Audio Codec Meets Language Model Objectives\narXiv: 2604.17852\nAuthors: Ho-Lam Chung, Yiming Chen, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We formalize the objective mismatch between reconstruction-trained audio codecs and prediction-trained language models, showing it inflates token uncertainty and language model perplexity.\n  2. We propose the LLM-Codec training framework using Future Token Prediction and Semantic Alignment as complementary regularizers to enhance token predictability and semantics.\n  3. We introduce a differentiable Gumbel-Softmax bridge that enables end-to-end gradient propagation through vector quantization while preserving discrete tokens in the forward pass.\n  4. We demonstrate that LLM-Codec improves speech coherence accuracy to 61.6% on SALMon and reduces token-level perplexity by 35 times compared to the base codec.\n  5. We show that LLM-Codec improves speech Mel distance by 5.0% on Codec-SUPERB-tiny, proving reconstruction fidelity and token predictability can be improved simultaneously.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/语义声学-语义\n=== 2510.25955 ===\n# SPEAR: A Unified SSL Framework for Learning Speech and Audio Representations\narXiv: 2510.25955\nAuthors: Xiaoyu Yang, Yifan Yang, Zengrui Jin, Ziyun Cui, Wen Wu, Baoxiang Li, Chao Zhang, Phil Woodland\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A self-supervised framework that distils complementary knowledge from a speech-focused SSL teacher and a general-audio SSL teacher into a single unified model.\n  2. The application of multi-codebook vector quantisation to continuous teacher representations to produce fine-grained discrete tokens capturing both semantic and acoustic information.\n  3. An asymmetric pre-training loss that jointly predicts heterogeneous representations given a masked input to effectively integrate them.\n  4. A novel token mixing mechanism to improve robustness in complex sound scenes.\n  5. Establishment of a new state-of-the-art on the SUPERB benchmark by surpassing WavLM Large on 12 out of 15 tasks while achieving competitive performance on the HEAR benchmark.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散, SSL/对比式\n=== 2509.11425 ===\n# FuseCodec: Semantic-Contextual Fusion and Supervision for Neural Codecs\narXiv: 2509.11425\nAuthors: Md Mubtasim Ahasan, Rafat Hasan Khan, Tasnim Mohiuddin, Aman Chadha, Tariq Iqbal, M Ashraful Amin, Amin Ahsan Ali, Md Mofijul Islam, A K M Mahbubur Rahman\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We introduce a unified speech tokenization framework with three codec variants integrating semantic and contextual information via latent fusion, global supervision, and temporal alignment.\n  2. Our approach substantially improves speech reconstruction and representation quality, establishing new state-of-the-art results on LibriSpeech and the Codec-SUPERB benchmark.\n  3. We validate the effectiveness of each component through extensive ablations and demonstrate practical utility in downstream text-to-speech generation.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-混合, 压缩/监督-有监督", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "46e84bdb-407d-4ec8-8a01-7e6e04372947", "uuid": "0c8b3e3b-1df2-4929-ada4-47fd258cff44", "timestamp": "2026-07-16T06:55:31.296Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2605.06407 ===\n# \\ WavCube: A Unified SSL-Derived Latent  Representation for   Speech Understanding, Reconstruction, and Generation\narXiv: 2605.06407\nAuthors: \nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavCube introduces a compact 128-dimensional continuous latent representation that unifies speech understanding, reconstruction, and generation within a single space by infusing acoustic details into a distilled semantic manifold.\n  2. A compress-then-enrich two-stage learning recipe is proposed to resolve the high-dimensional redundancy and acoustic deficit inherent in SSL features, systematically transforming them into unified representations.\n  3. The compress stage utilizes a semantic auto-encoder bottleneck to distill frozen WavLM features into a compact, diffusion-friendly subspace while filtering off-manifold redundancy.\n  4. The enrich stage injects fine-grained acoustic details via end-to-end speech reconstruction while a semantic anchoring loss prevents drift from the original semantic manifold.\n  5. Extensive evaluations show WavCube closely approaches WavLM performance on SUPERB despite an 8x dimensional compression while matching acoustic representations in reconstruction fidelity.\n  6. WavCube achieves state-of-the-art zero-shot TTS performance with significantly fas