{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bf27b0db23ffce67", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# SPEAR: A Unified SSL Framework for Learning Speech and Audio Representations\narXiv: 2510.25955\nAuthors: Xiaoyu Yang, Yifan Yang, Zengrui Jin, Ziyun Cui, Wen Wu, Baoxiang Li, Chao Zhang, Phil Woodland\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A self-supervised framework that distils complementary knowledge from a speech-focused SSL teacher and a general-audio SSL teacher into a single unified model.\n  2. The application of multi-codebook vector quantisation to continuous teacher representations to produce fine-grained discrete tokens capturing both semantic and acoustic information.\n  3. An asymmetric pre-training loss that jointly predicts heterogeneous representations given a masked input to effectively integrate them.\n  4. A novel token mixing mechanism to improve robustness in complex sound scenes.\n  5. Establishment of a new state-of-the-art on the SUPERB benchmark by surpassing WavLM Large on 12 out of 15 tasks while achieving competitive performance on the HEAR benchmark.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散, SSL/对比式\n---\n# WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing\narXiv: 2110.13900\nAuthors: Sanyuan Chen, Chengyi Wang, Zhengyang Chen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Jinyu Li, Naoyuki Kanda, Takuya Yoshioka, Xiong Xiao, Jian Wu, Long Zhou, Shuo Ren, Yanmin Qian, Yao Qian, Jian Wu, Michael Zeng, Xiangzhan Yu, Furu Wei\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavLM introduces a general pre-trained model for full stack speech processing tasks, moving beyond the focus on specific task groups like ASR in prior self-supervised learning works.\n  2. A masked speech denoising and prediction framework is proposed to jointly learn speech content modeling and denoising, effectively improving performance on non-ASR tasks such as speaker verification, diarization, and separation.\n  3. Gated relative position bias is integrated into the Transformer structure to adaptively adjust relative position biases based on current speech content, enhancing sequence ordering capture and ASR performance.\n  4. The self-supervised speech pre-training data is scaled up to 94k hours from diverse domains, alleviating audiobook data bias and improving model robustness.\n  5. State-of-the-art results are achieved on the SUPERB benchmark and representative benchmarks for speaker verification, speech separation, and speaker diarization, with models and code publicly released.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "46e84bdb-407d-4ec8-8a01-7e6e04372947", "uuid": "1eed1bce-7a9b-4c31-8527-a97492c4dcaf", "timestamp": "2026-07-16T06:59:11.942Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# SPEAR: A Unified SSL Framework for Learning Speech and Audio Representations\narXiv: 2510.25955\nAuthors: Xiaoyu Yang, Yifan Yang, Zengrui Jin, Ziyun Cui, Wen Wu, Baoxiang Li, Chao Zhang, Phil Woodland\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A self-supervised framework that distils complementary knowledge from a speech-focused SSL teacher and a general-audio SSL teacher into a single unified model.\n  2. The application of multi-codebook vector quantisation to continuous teacher representations to produce fine-grained discrete tokens capturing both semantic and acoustic information.\n  3. An asymmetric pre-training loss that jointly predicts heterogeneous representations given a masked input to effectively integrate them.\n  4. A novel token mixing mechanism to improve robustness in complex sound scenes.\n  5. Establishment of a new state-of-the-art on the SUPERB benchmark by surpassing WavLM Large on 12 out of 15 tasks while achieving competitive performance on the HEAR benchmark.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散, SSL/对比式\n---\n# WavLM: Large-Scale Self-Supervised Pre-Training for Full Stack Speech Processing\narXiv: 2110.13900\nAuthors: Sanyuan Chen, Chengyi Wang, Zhengyang Chen, Yu Wu, Shujie Liu, Zhuo Chen, Jinyu Li, Naoyuki Kanda, Takuya Yoshioka, Xiong Xiao, Jian Wu, Long Zhou, Shuo Ren, Yanmin Qian, Yao Qian, Jian Wu, Michael Zeng, Xiangzhan Yu, Furu Wei\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavLM introduces a general pre-trained model for full stack speech processing tasks, moving beyond the focus on specific task groups like ASR in prior self-supervised learning works.\n  2. A masked speech denoising and prediction framework is proposed to jointly learn speech content modeling and denoising, effectively improving performance on non-ASR tasks such as speaker verification, diarization, and separation.\n  3. Gated relative position bias is integrated into the Transformer structure to adaptively adjust relative position biases based on current speech content, enhancing sequence ordering capture and ASR performance.\n  4. The self-supervised speech pre-training data is scaled up to 94k hours from diverse domains, alleviating audiobook data bias and improving model robustness.\n  5. State-of-the-art results are achieved on the SUPERB benchmark and representative benchmarks for speaker verification, speech separation, and speaker diarization, with models and code publicly released.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
