{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784185848957", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Review complete. Summary of findings:\n\n**Paper**: \"Rethinking Speech Foundation Model Fine-tuning: Better SFT or Better Match?\" (arXiv 2607.13864v1)\n\n**Type**: Analysis型 — 系统实证分析 SFT 配方排名的 checkpoint 依赖性\n\n**Verdict**: Borderline (5.2/10)\n\n**Key strengths**:\n- 280+ experiments (~10,000 GPU-hours) across 3 SUPERB tasks × 9 SSL checkpoints × 8 SFT configs × multi-seed\n- Evidence independent (official SUPERB pipeline, no judge contamination)\n- Core phenomenon (top-group instability across checkpoints) is real and documented in Table 2/3\n\n**Key weaknesses**:\n- \"Elicitation match\" explanatory framework lacks independent mechanism evidence (no representation analysis, no probing, no activation visualization)\n- Multi-seed validation covers only 3 base checkpoints (27 rows in Table 3)\n- No code repo, no raw prediction files released\n- Only 3 classification tasks; IC near-ceiling (~99%), limiting discriminative power\n- ACL 2023 \"Measuring the Instability of Fine-Tuning\" is a direct NLP predecessor for seed-variance analysis\n\n**Wiki/tool results**: OMC wiki returned empty for all 6 queries. paper-wiki found 17 related speech papers (WavLM, SPEAR, WavCube) but none covering SFT recipe instability. free-search confirmed ACL 2023 prior work and EMO-SUPERB's finding that 80.77% of SER papers are irreproducible, supporting the reproducibility concern."}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "46e84bdb-407d-4ec8-8a01-7e6e04372947", "uuid": "1e049248-1a64-4138-974a-7d9f5f85d819"}
